# Worker Common Rules

## Research Items (project.yaml)

`project.yaml`'s `items:` contains a nested structure of items. Each item has a `kind` (narrative, task, question, conjecture, example, caution, gap, observation, etc.) and a `status` (open, active, partial, resolved, reframed, dropped).

The `detail` field is a free-text supplement to the status, describing nuances that the structured `status` alone cannot convey. For `resolved` items in particular, describe the rigor and confidence level — this helps PI in subsequent sessions judge how much to rely on the result. Include explanations for `open` or `dropped` items as well when relevant.

Item status determination requires the context of the entire research and is PI's responsibility.

- **Read-only** (only PI writes)
- To propose a status change, describe the rationale in your deliverable file
- Honest reporting is paramount: never propose resolved for something that isn't actually resolved

## Inter-Agent Communication

Loading large amounts of data into prompts wastes context window. Writing to files allows reading only the necessary parts.

- **Input**: Receive task instructions and file paths from PI; Read the necessary data yourself
- **Output**: Write deliverables to files and return `DONE: {deliverable path}` as the Task return value
- Never load raw data directly into prompts — always communicate via files

## Logs (Progress Records for Humans)

Write a work summary to `logs/{agent}_{timestamp}.md`.
This is a record for humans to review progress later, not a decision input for PI.

## Research Notes Format

`research/notes/` is an Obsidian-compatible wiki-linked knowledge base maintained by PI. These notes are **read-only** for worker agents (same rule as project.yaml). Understanding the syntax lets you follow cross-references and assess the reliability of claims.

- **Wiki-links**: `[[note-name]]`, `[[note-name#heading]]`, `[[note-name|display text]]` — references to other note files. To follow a link, find the file matching the note-name (with `.md` extension) under `research/notes/`
- **Tags**: `#tag-name` — inline classification labels (e.g., `#conjecture`, `#verified`, `#key-result`)
- **Verification status tags**: `[sympy]`, `[numerical]`, `[limiting case]`, `[literature: arXiv:XXXX]`, `[unverified]` — indicate how a claim was verified. Treat `[unverified]` claims with appropriate caution; do not cite them as established results

## Constraints

- Write equations in LaTeX notation (inline: `$...$`, display: `$$...$$`). Do not embed raw variable names or expressions in prose — always wrap them in `$...$`. Prioritize readability in Markdown files; use `$$` instead of LaTeX environment names
- AskUserQuestion is prohibited (users are often away during `/run` and `/write`, and asking questions interrupts the session. However, you may respond if the user initiates communication)
- No writing outside the project directory
- Each agent writes only to its designated output location (see individual agent definitions)
